Common CSS Issues and Debugging Techniques
CSS can be a powerful tool for styling web pages, but it can also be a source of frustration if issues arise. Here are some common CSS problems and how to debug them using browser developer tools:

Common CSS Issues
Conflicting Styles: Multiple stylesheets or inline styles can override each other.
Specificity Issues: CSS rules with higher specificity can override less specific ones.
Typographical Errors: Incorrect syntax or spelling can prevent styles from being applied.
Browser Compatibility: Different browsers may render CSS differently.
Layout Problems: Elements may not be positioned or sized correctly.
Debugging CSS with Browser Developer Tools
Inspect Elements:

Right-click on an element and select "Inspect" or use the shortcut (usually F12).
This opens the developer tools console, where you can examine the HTML structure and CSS applied to the element.
Identify CSS Problems:

Check for Conflicting Styles: Look for multiple rules that target the same element.
Inspect Specificity: Use the browser's developer tools to determine the specificity of CSS rules.
Verify Syntax: Ensure there are no typos or errors in your CSS code.
Check for Browser Compatibility: Test your website in different browsers to identify any rendering issues.
Analyze Layout: Inspect the element's dimensions, positioning, and any parent or child elements that might be affecting its layout.
Test Changes Live:

Make changes to the CSS code directly in the developer tools console.
The changes will be applied immediately to the element, allowing you to see the results in real time.
Example: A Misaligned Image
Problem: An image on a web page is positioned incorrectly, overlapping with the text below it.

Debugging Steps:

Inspect the Image: Right-click on the image and select "Inspect."
Check for Conflicting Styles: Examine the CSS rules applied to the image and its parent elements. Look for any margin, padding, or positioning properties that might be causing the overlap.
Adjust the CSS: In the developer tools console, try modifying the margin-bottom property of the image to add more space between it and the text.
Test Changes: Observe the changes in real time to see if the image is now positioned correctly.
Example CSS Modification:

CSS
img {
    margin-bottom: 20px;
}
Use code with caution.

By following these steps and using browser developer tools effectively, you can efficiently debug CSS issues and ensure that your web pages are visually appealing and functional.